      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Read</span><span class="meta-value">7 min</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">City pages, location pages</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local landing pages</strong> are dedicated web pages optimized to rank for "[service] in [location]" search queries, each targeting a specific geographic area your business serves. A plumber covering 10 cities builds 10 separate pages — one per city. Pages with genuine local content rank 3-5 positions higher than templated versions, according to Moz research.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-5 positions vs templates</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Unique content needed</div>
            <div class="tms-value">At least 60% per page</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The difference between a local landing page that ranks and a doorway page that gets penalized is specificity. Google's algorithm has gotten very good at distinguishing pages that genuinely serve a location from pages that just mention it.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are local landing pages?</h2>
        <p>Local landing pages are service pages on your website built specifically for one geographic area. Each page targets the "[service] + [location]" keyword cluster for that city, neighborhood, or region — and contains content that is genuinely useful to someone in that area.</p>
        <p>Google's John Mueller has explicitly warned against "doorway pages": pages that are essentially the same content with swapped city names. The way to build local landing pages that rank is to make each one genuinely different. That means including:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Local customer testimonials and reviews from that area</li>
          <li>Team members or service crews who cover that location</li>
          <li>Specific neighborhoods or landmarks within the service area</li>
          <li>Region-specific service details (climate-specific HVAC needs, local code requirements)</li>
          <li>Local statistics, case studies, or area-relevant data</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Moz research finding</div>
          <p>Moz's local ranking factors research shows that local landing pages with <strong>unique, area-specific content rank 3-5 positions higher</strong> than near-identical city-swap versions. That gap represents a massive difference in visibility and traffic for service-area businesses.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why local landing pages matter for SEO</h2>
        <p>A single service page targeting all cities leaves ranking potential on the table. Local landing pages unlock geographic coverage systematically:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Geographic coverage expansion.</strong> Each page creates a distinct ranking opportunity for a specific city. A plumber serving 10 cities with one page competes in all 10 markets poorly. With 10 pages, they compete in each market properly.</li>
          <li><strong>Local pack support.</strong> Location-specific pages on your website strengthen the relevance signals that feed into your Google Maps ranking. Your GBP and your website need to agree on what areas you serve.</li>
          <li><strong>High-intent organic traffic.</strong> "[Service] in [city]" queries carry strong purchase intent. Someone searching "emergency dentist Portland" is not browsing — they need an appointment now.</li>
          <li><strong>Service-area business reach.</strong> If you don't have a physical location in every city you serve, a local landing page is how you establish search presence there without a storefront.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to build local landing pages that rank</h2>
        <p>The structure of a winning local landing page follows a consistent pattern.</p>

        <h3>SEO elements — the technical foundation</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Title tag — city name prominent near the front</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">Plumber in Austin, TX | Emergency Plumbing Services</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># URL slug — city in the slug</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">/plumber-austin/</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># H1 — exact local keyword match</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">Plumber in Austin, TX</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Schema — LocalBusiness with service area</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">areaServed:</span> <span class="uf-new">Austin, TX</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Content that differentiates — the ranking factor</h3>
        <p>Each page needs at minimum 60% unique content. The boilerplate you share across all location pages (company history, general service descriptions) should not exceed 40% of the page. Differentiate with:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>3-5 testimonials from customers in that specific city</li>
          <li>A list of neighborhoods covered within that service area</li>
          <li>Staff member profiles for the team that serves the area</li>
          <li>Local context: "Austin's clay soil causes more slab leaks than any other Texas city — here's what that means for your plumbing"</li>
          <li>An embedded Google Map showing the service coverage area</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Avoiding the doorway page trap</h3>
        <p>The doorway page test: remove the city name from your page. If the remaining content is essentially identical to your other location pages, Google will classify it as a doorway page and either not rank it or penalize your domain. If the remaining content still tells a story specific to that area, you've built a real local landing page.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Local landing page types</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Target query</th><th>Content depth</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>City page</strong></td>
                <td>[service] in [city]</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Full — 800-1500 words</td>
                <td>Primary service areas</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Neighborhood page</strong></td><td>[service] near [neighborhood]</td><td class="cell-yes">Medium — 500-800 words</td><td>High-density metros</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>County / region page</strong></td><td>[service] [county] county</td><td class="cell-meh">Medium</td><td>Rural or wide-area businesses</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Service area hub</strong></td><td>Areas we serve</td><td class="cell-meh">Hub linking to city pages</td><td>Internal linking structure</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Doorway page (avoid)</strong></td><td>[service] [city] (templated)</td><td class="cell-no">Thin — swapped city name only</td><td>Never — Google penalty risk</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real local landing page examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — HVAC company, 10 cities</h3>
        <p>A heating and cooling company creates 10 city landing pages. The Austin page includes Austin-specific summer heat data, reviews from Austin homeowners, a coverage map showing the Austin neighborhoods they service, and a note about Austin's specific AC load requirements from the Texas heat. Each other city page is equally localized. Result: they rank on page 1 for 8 of their 10 target city keywords within 90 days.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Personal injury law firm, neighborhood targeting</h3>
        <p>A law firm creates 15 neighborhood pages across their metro area. Each page discusses accident statistics specific to that neighborhood, nearby court information, and case studies from intersections in the area. They use theStacc to publish supporting blog content that internally links to each neighborhood page, building the authority of each one over time.</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Internal link structure reinforcing neighborhood pages</span><br>
          /blog/east-austin-car-accident-statistics/ <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">/personal-injury-east-austin/</span><br>
          /blog/south-congress-intersection-accidents/ <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">/personal-injury-south-congress/</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local landing pages vs doorway pages — how Google tells them apart</h2>
        <p>Both look similar to an untrained eye. Google's classifiers are not fooled.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Local landing page (safe to build)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Unique testimonials from that city's customers</li>
              <li>Area-specific service details and coverage map</li>
              <li>Local staff profiles or contact information</li>
              <li>City-specific data, stats, or case studies</li>
              <li>Minimum 60% content unique to that location</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Doorway page (Google penalty risk)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Same content as all other city pages, city name swapped</li>
              <li>No genuine local information or context</li>
              <li>Thin — under 300 words with no unique value</li>
              <li>No customer reviews or local trust signals</li>
              <li>Mass-produced at scale with no editorial review</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for local landing pages</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>One page per city you actively serve.</strong> Never create pages for locations you cannot actually service — Google may treat that as deceptive, and users will bounce when they realise you can't help them.</li>
          <li><strong>City name in the URL slug.</strong> <code>/plumber-austin/</code> sends a clearer geographic signal than <code>/locations/page-14/</code>.</li>
          <li><strong>Collect location-specific reviews proactively.</strong> After every job in a new city, ask the customer to mention the city or neighborhood in their review. These feed both your GBP and your landing page credibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Add a Google Map embed.</strong> Embedded maps are a local relevance signal and improve engagement metrics. Center it on the city, not your head office if they differ.</li>
          <li><strong>Include LocalBusiness schema.</strong> Add schema markup specifying the <code>areaServed</code> for each page. This gives Google structured data to confirm the geographic scope.</li>
          <li><strong>Build internal links from blog content.</strong> Every city page should receive 3-5 internal links from relevant blog posts targeting local queries. This builds page authority without external link building.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit for doorway page signals quarterly.</strong> As you scale to 20, 50, or 100 city pages, content drift makes pages more similar over time. Audit every quarter and refresh the bottom-performing pages with new local content.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — templating at scale</div>
          <p>A business builds 50 city pages using a template that swaps the city name in 4 places and calls it done. Google's duplicate content detection finds the pattern, ignores most of the pages, and may flag the domain for doorway page tactics. The fix: add at minimum 3 genuinely local elements per page before publishing — even a paragraph of local context and 2 area-specific customer quotes are enough to differentiate.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common local landing page mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Creating pages for areas you don't serve</strong> — misleads users and can attract Google quality actions.</li>
          <li><strong>Sharing phone numbers across all city pages</strong> — use a local phone number or at minimum a direct line for each service area, not one central number for every location.</li>
          <li><strong>No internal linking</strong> — city pages buried at depth 4 in your site hierarchy will not rank. Ensure every city page is reachable within 2-3 clicks from your homepage.</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate meta descriptions</strong> — "We are the best plumber in [city]" scaled across 50 pages with only the city name changed triggers duplicate meta detection. Write unique meta descriptions per page.</li>
          <li><strong>Publishing all pages on the same day</strong> — launching 50 thin city pages simultaneously looks spammy. Build and publish in batches of 5-10, ensuring quality before moving to the next batch.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How many local landing pages should I create?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Create one page per city or major neighborhood you actively serve. Don't create pages for areas where you can't actually provide service — Google may flag that as deceptive. A service company covering 10 cities needs 10 pages. Expand to neighborhood pages for your highest-priority markets.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Will local landing pages cause duplicate content issues?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Only if the content is duplicated. Each page needs at minimum 60% unique content. Shared boilerplate like company overview paragraphs should stay under 40% of the page. Use unique testimonials, area-specific data, and locally relevant information to differentiate. Google won't flag pages as duplicate content if each provides distinct value.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do I need a physical address for each local landing page?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Service area businesses can create local pages for areas they serve without having offices there. Include your service area coverage, response times for that area, and local team assignments. Avoid faking addresses — Google detects and penalizes fake business locations.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What makes a local landing page different from a doorway page?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A doorway page is a thin, templated page with swapped city names and no unique value. A proper local landing page includes area-specific content: local customer reviews, neighborhood coverage maps, region-specific services, and real local context. The test: remove the city name — if the page reads identically to your other location pages, it is a doorway page.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What SEO elements must every local landing page include?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Include the city name in the title tag, H1, meta description, and URL. Add LocalBusiness schema markup with the correct service area. Include an embedded Google Map centered on the target location. Link internally to your main service pages and city-specific blog content.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

